  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improving Diaspora Organisation Services</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since 2000 Africa Foundation Stone (AFS) has provided educational support for young people from ethnic minority and disadvantaged backgrounds in North London. It has an impressive record of achievement, attaining a 96% pass rate in GCSEs and A levels. In 2005 AFS began working in the Cameroon with 10 local organisations to support access for street children to primary education and vocational training and improve child protection and policies. AFS has found that success in the Cameroon and demand for their services from the Cameroon Government and local partners has stretched their organisational capacity to respond to its limits of effectiveness. While they have been successful in securing grants from Comic Relief (CR) and DFID, they have not effectively secured funds to build their organisational capacity. In 2010 AFS undertook strategic partnership reviews with its Cameroonian partners and a VSO consultant undertook an OD assessment. The findings emphasised that project M&amp;E and associated IT systems must be improved to ensure effective tracking of impact, quality reporting and learning. AFS believe a strategic visioning exercise and upgrading of UK staff, volunteer and trustee skills in fundraising and project management is required to underpin and sustain these improvements.</narrative>
  </description>
